org.cicirello.sequences

Class ObjectSequence<E extends java.lang.Comparable<E>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.cicirello.sequences.ObjectSequence<E>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Sequence<E>

    public final class ObjectSequence<E extends java.lang.Comparable<E>>
extends java.lang.Object
implements Sequence<E>
    An ObjectSequence is a sequence of values of any one object type, provided the objects are Comparable. It provides support for comparing elements within a single sequence, as well as for comparing elements between a pair of sequences. Its primary purpose within this library is in support of algorithms on sequences, such as the computation of distance metrics found in the classes of the org.cicirello.sequences.distance package.
    Since:
    1.1

      • ObjectSequence

        public ObjectSequence(E[] array)
        Constructs an ObjectSequence from a given array of objects. The array is not cloned, and the sequence object holds a reference to the very array. This allows changing contents of array either directly or via the methods of this sequence class.

      • search

        public int search(E element)
        Searches the Sequence for an element using a search algorithm whose runtime is O(lg n), such as binary search. The Sequence must be sorted prior to calling search. If it is not sorted, the result is undefined. If the Sequence contains the element multiple times, there is no guarantee which will be found.
        Specified by:
        search in interface Sequence<E extends java.lang.Comparable<E>>
        Parameters:
        element - The target element.
        Returns:
        index of the element, if it is contained in the sequence; otherwise, (-(insertion point) - 1). The insertion point is defined as the point at which the element would be inserted into the sequence if you wanted to maintain sorted order: the index of the first element greater than the element, or length() if all elements in the sequence are less than the specified element. Note that this guarantees that the return value will be >= 0 if and only if the element is found.
